data.content:
## Migration: `TimedExecutor` → .NET 8

### Why this breaks

In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is a no-op. The entire preemptive abort model is gone.

### Pattern classification

Your code is **Timeout enforcement** — aborting a thread that exceeds a time limit. The replacement is cooperative cancellation via `CancellationTokenSource.CancelAfter`.

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Task.WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException on timeout
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            throw new AggregateException(ex.InnerException!);
        }
    }

    // Preferred: async overload for modern callers
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout, CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return await task.WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        // If externalToken was cancelled, OperationCanceledException propagates as-is
    }
}
```

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Detail |
|---------|--------|
| **Cancellation isn't instant** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, the work **keeps running** until it checks the token. If `work()` is a tight CPU loop that never checks, it won't stop. Pass `CancellationToken` into the work and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at checkpoints. |
| **Dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaking it causes timer leaks. Always `using`. |
| **Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`** | The `when` filter distinguishes timeout from external cancellation. |
| **`Task.WaitAsync` doesn't kill the task** | It unblocks the *caller*, but the background task still runs to completion. This matches the old behavior where `Thread.Abort` could fail silently. |

### If `work` truly can't cooperate

For uncooperative code (e.g., third-party library, native call), **no in-process mechanism can forcibly stop it** in modern .NET. Move it to a child process and use `Process.Kill`:

```csharp
// Last resort — out-of-process execution
var process = Process.Start("WorkerApp.exe", args);
if (!process.WaitForExit(timeout))
{
    process.Kill(entireProcessTree: true);
    throw new TimeoutException("...");
}
```

### Making existing work cooperate

Update your work delegates to accept and check a token:

```csharp
// Before (uncooperative — won't actually stop on timeout)
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => {
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
        Process(item);
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// After (cooperative — stops promptly)
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => {
    foreach (var item in hugeList)
    {
        cts.Token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return result;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

The fundamental shift: .NET Framework let you kill threads externally; .NET 8 requires code to **opt in** to cancellation.
